In this document, we intend to investigate the following key questions, assuming a fixed array of \(10^6\) SNPs:

  • When should I be concerned about Winnerâ€™s Curse or about my association estimates being more extreme than their corresponding true effect sizes?
  • If I adjust SNP-trait association estimates using a Winnerâ€™s Curse method, how much should I expect this to improve the association estimates of significant SNPs?
  • If I do use a Winnerâ€™s Curse method, which one should I use?

We first focus on a quantitative trait in which SNP effect sizes follow a normal distribution.

When is Winnerâ€™s Curse a problem?

In this section, we look at the average number of significant SNPs, the average proportion of these significant SNPs that have association estimates more extreme than their true effect size and the average MSE of significant SNPs at two different thresholds; the common genome-wide significance threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-8}\) and a higher threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-4}\). We consider these properties under certain combinations of values for the following parameters:

  1. sample size - n_samples
  2. heritability - h2
  3. polygenicity, i.e.Â proportion of effect SNPs - prop_effect
  4. selection coefficient - S

â˜… It is important to note here that for scenarios 1, 9 and 17, very few significant SNPs are detected on average. In some instances, we may even find that no SNPs are deemed significant at a threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-8}\). We must keep this observation in mind going forward as we investigate the performance of methods under these three scenarios.

For both thresholds, the average number of significant SNPs increases as sample size increases, as expected. It also increases with heritability. However, the effect of changing prop_effect is more interesting. Decreasing the proportion of effect SNPs from 0.01 to 0.001 results in the number of significant SNPs increasing for a sample size of 30,000 while we witness the number of SNPs passing the genome-wide significance threshold decreasing for a larger sample size of 300,000.

Furthermore, increasing sample size and increasing heritability from 0.3 to 0.8 all tend to decrease the fraction of significant SNPs whose estimates are more extreme than their true effect size. Decreasing polygenicity from 0.01 to 0.001 also has this same effect at a significance threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-8}\).

As sample size increases from 30,000 to 300,000 in all scenarios, prop_x, the proportion of significant SNPs which have been found to be significantly overestimated, decreases. This is a strong indicator that as the value of n_samples increases, we expect the bias induced by Winnerâ€™s Curse to be less of a problem among significant SNPs. However, this could also be due to the fact that as sample size increases, the number of significant SNPs passing the genome-wide significance threshold of 5e-8 also increases.

In order to gain a better insight into the information detailed in the above table, we simulate a single set of GWAS summary statistics and plot \(z\) vs \(\text{bias}\) in which \(\text{bias} = \hat\beta - \beta\) for each of the 24 different scenarios. On all figures, the bright red line corresponds to the significance threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-8}\) while the darker red line relates to \(5 \times 10^{-4}\). The points corresponding to SNPs which are significantly overestimated and are significant at a threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-4}\) are coloured in navy .

Evaluating methods using a significance threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-8}\)

Using the code detailed in norm_5e-8_100sim.R and a total of 100 simulations, we evaluated six different Winnerâ€™s Curse methods across each of the 24 scenarios using the following three bias evaluation metrics:

  1. The average fraction of significant SNPs in which their association estimates have been improved due to method implementation - flb
  2. The average change in average MSE of significant SNPs due to method implementation - mse
  3. The average relative change in average MSE of significant SNPs due to method implementation - rel_mse

Note: All averages are obtained over only those simulations in which at least one significant SNP was detected.

Firstly, the fraction of \(n\) significant SNPs in which their association estimates have been improved due to method implementation may be mathematically described as: \[\frac{1}{n} \; \sum_{i=1}^{n}\mathbb{I} \left\{ \left| \hat\beta_i - \beta_i \right| > \left|\hat\beta_{\text{adj,}i} - \beta_i\right| \right\},\]in which \(\left| \frac{\hat\beta_i}{\hat\sigma_i} \right| > Z_{\frac{\alpha}{2}}\) for all \(i = 1,...,n\), where \(\hat\beta_i\) is the estimated naive effect size of SNP \(i\), \(\beta_i\) is its true effect size and \(\hat\beta_{\text{adj,}i}\) is its new effect size estimate obtained as a result of application of the Winnerâ€™s Curse adjustment method of interest. The significance threshold is represented by \(\alpha\).

Using the same notation, the average MSE over \(n\) significant SNPs is defined as: \[\frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_i - \beta_i)^2.\]g Thus, using the above, we may formally define the change in average MSE of significant SNPs as: \[\frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_{\text{adj,}i} - \beta_i)^2 - \frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_i - \beta_i)^2\] and the relative change in average MSE of significant SNPs as: \[\frac{\frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_{\text{adj,}i} - \beta_i)^2 - \frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_i - \beta_i)^2}{\frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_i - \beta_i)^2}.\]

\(~\)

Results of the simulations are plotted. We noted that the selection parameter, S, does not in fact have much of an impact and thus, all plots merely include those scenarios in which S is fixed at 0. Error bars are also included in the plots. These figures allow us to see more clearly the scenarios in which it would be beneficial to apply a Winnerâ€™s Curse correction method and also, provide us with a better indication of which method we should use.

A replication method which selects significant SNPs from a discovery GWAS and then uses a replication GWAS of the same size to obtain association estimates for these SNPs is also included in the plots. This can be viewed as acting as a form of benchmark for the other methods.

Observations and discussion of above simulations

It is worth noting from the above simulations how the Winnerâ€™s Curse methods tend to break down, or equivalently, no longer make improvements based on the third evaluation metric, rel_mse when the proportion of effect SNPs is 0.001. This is a measure of polygenicity. That said, the empirical Bayes method performs very similar to just taking a replication estimate when the replication sample is of the same size as the discovery GWAS, i.e.Â n_samples is equivalent in both data sets and as we will see later, the empirical Bayes will outperform the replication method when the replication GWAS sample size becomes smaller than that of the discovery, at this threshold of 5e-8. This observation strongly supports the use of empirical Bayes as a Winnerâ€™s Curse adjustment method, particularly when a replication GWAS is not available. The consistency of the empirical Bayes method is what makes it stand out above the other considered methods. Unlike the bootstrap and FIQT, it is rare that it will result in an increase in the relative average MSE or average MSE over all significant SNPs. For that reason, employing this method gives us confidence that we have not adjusted our estimated effect sizes so that they are now less accurate, regardless of the underlying genetic architecture or number of samples.

For prop_effect = 0.01, our proposed bootstrap method for summary statistics performs in a comparable manner to both empirical Bayes and the replication method. However, the bootstrap method ceases to perform as well at obtaining less biased association estimates when the proportion of effect SNPs is reduced to 0.001.

On all occasions, the conditional likelihood methods tend to perform poorly compared to the other methods. This is likely due to the fact that the conditional likelihood approach can over-correct estimated effect sizes, especially those that lie close to the significance threshold.

Clearly, even though we also look at using a significance threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-4}\), it is the genome-wide significance threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-8}\) that is of most interest to us as using the higher threshold of \(5 \times 10^{-4}\) often results in the detection of many false positives.

Comparison of the Empirical Bayes method with the true Bayes rule

In this section, we investigate comparing our empirical Bayes method with the true Bayes rule, given that our simulated true effect size distribution is used as the prior. This can allow us to identify the scenarios under which the empirical Bayes method performs almost optimally. If the effect sizes are standardized, i.e.Â we consider \(z = \frac{\hat{\beta}}{\hat{se(\hat\beta)}}\), the true Bayes rule is known to be the optimal function of the data, at a single SNP, in minimizing population mean squared errors. In fact, it is also optimal in minimizing mean squared error over a subset of the data space, \(\left| Z>c \right|\) say. The empirical Bayes approach aims to construct the Bayes rule. However, it fails to do this precisely as the exact marginal density of \(z\)-scores is not available.

If we denote the prior as \(p(\mu)\) and the marginal density of \(z\)-scores as \(f(z|\mu)\), then the Bayes rule is given as: \[f(\mu|z) = \frac{p(\mu) f(z|\mu)}{\int{p(\mu) f(z|\mu) d\mu}}.\] Thus, we can then write: \[E(\mu | z) = \int{\mu f(\mu | z) d\mu} = \frac{\int{\mu p(\mu) f(z|\mu)}}{\int{p(\mu)f(z|\mu)}}.\]

As our prior, \(p(\mu)\), has a point mass, it is difficult to integrate the above. Therefore, we choose to discretize the range of \(\mu\)s and calculate these integrals via summation. We then obtain: \[E(\mu | z) = \frac{\sum\mu_{\text{mid}} \cdot p(\mu_{\text{mid}}) \cdot \phi(z - \mu_{mid})}{\sum p(\mu_{\text{mid}}) \cdot \phi(z-\mu_{\text{mid}})}\]in which \(\mu_{\text{mid}}\) is the midpoint of the interval, \(p(\mu_{\text{mid}})\) is the fraction of total SNPs falling in that interval and \(\phi\) is the standard normal density.

We first perform similar simulations to as those in previous sections with a normal effect size distribution, computing the mean relative change in average MSE over all significant SNPs for both the empirical Bayes method and the true Bayes rule which we have described here.

Measuring the degree of Winnerâ€™s Curse across the various scenarios

In this final section, using 100 simulations, we have computed \[\frac{\text{MSE}_{\text{naive}}}{\text{MSE}_{\text{rep}}} = \frac{\frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_{\text{naive,}i} - \beta_i)^2}{\frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\hat\beta_{\text{rep,}i} - \beta_i)^2}\] over the top 10 significant SNPs and the top 100 significant SNPs for each combination of our considered scenarios and three effect size distributions: normal, skewed and bimodal, for a quantitative trait. This can be thought of as a measure of the extent of the winnerâ€™s curse induced bias in each case, in which it is important to note that the number of samples in the replication data set is equivalent to that in the discovery. As above, the first set of results relate to where we have looked at just the top 10 significant SNPs. Note that we have merely plotted results for neutral selection as we have witnessed that the selection coefficient, S does not seem to have a great impact on our findings. The fact that we witness in every scenario that the average of \(\frac{\text{MSE}_{\text{naive}}}{\text{MSE}_{\text{rep}}}\) across our 100 simulations is greater than 1 is certain evidence of the existence of winnerâ€™s curse. However, the extent of the bias induced by winnerâ€™s curse varies drastically depending on the values of our parameters of interest and the distribution of true effects. Most noticeably, it is a normal effect size distribution that suffers the greatest out of our three considered distributions. In particular, a large degree of winnerâ€™s curse is seen when the heritability is 0.3, the proportion of true effect SNPs is 0.01 and we have 30,000 samples. This is the case for all three distributions. The same pattern is visible for the case in which we consider the top 10 SNPs and for the case in which we take a look at the top 100 SNPs. We chose to compare this metric for a fixed number of SNPs in each scenario instead of for just those SNPs that reached the specified threshold in each scenario to ensure that witnessed changes in \(\frac{\text{MSE}_{\text{naive}}}{\text{MSE}_{\text{rep}}}\) were not due to the differing numbers of significant SNPs.

The very large error bar visible here for the empirical Bayes method is most likely due to the fact that in that situation, very few SNPs pass the significance threshold and sometimes there may even not be any SNPs deemed significant. We see here that the best method seems to be the empirical Bayes method when it is applied to \((\hat\beta_{\text{com}}, \sigma_{\text{com}})\) in which:\[\hat\beta_{\text{com}} = \frac{\sigma_2^2 \hat\beta_1 + \sigma_1^2 \hat\beta_2}{\sigma_1^2 + \sigma_2^2} \; \;\ \; \text{and} \; \; \; \sigma^2_{\text{com}} = \frac{\sigma_1^2 \sigma_2^2}{\sigma_1^2 + \sigma_2^2}.\] Interestingly, UMVCUE behaves almost identically to just using the replication estimates. We see that the conditional likelihood methods, the MSE minimization method (particularly when the spline approach is employed) and the empirical Bayes combination method all ensure that the average MSE over all significant SNPs in the discovery GWAS is reduced in comparison to using just the replication data set or UMVCUE.

The fact that the results here remain quite similar to those that we viewed previously under a normal distribution of true effect sizes is reassuring. In fact, we note the slightly improved performance of the empirical Bayes method which uses only the discovery GWAS with this bimodal distribution. Again, the combined empirical Bayes approach makes the greatest improvement to the average MSE of significant SNPs in almost all scenarios while the UMVCUE method continues to behave in a very similar manner to using only the replication GWAS to obtain estimates for the effect sizes.
